title: mafafojr
author: mafafojr
content: Why can't I have my Bitcoin? bitcoin node debug.loghttps://drive.google.com/file/d/1-S1XSujzRa5kstwmqnj-KkulQ3dNnaki/view?usp=sharing

comments.author: NotATether
comments.body: I do not trust that link enough to open it, but I will answer that Bitcoin Core debug.log doesn't keep track of your wallet balance and so doesn't tell you when you have mined some Bitcoins.

comments.author: NotATether
comments.body: As I said, the debug.log does not show people any information about them sending or receiving bitcoins. The debug output you posted shows Bitcoin Core receiving and verifying blocks.

comments.author: mafafojr
comments.body: i just know that i mined plenty of Bitcoin very early.

comments.author: NotATether
comments.body: Quote from: mafafojr on October 13, 2022, 07:13:26 AMi just know that i mined plenty of Bitcoin very early.I do not know whether old versions of Bitcoin Core recorded when you mine a block using their built-in miner (they probably did but I'm not 100% sure). But these debug.log entries are from March 2022 - look at the timestamps. These can't possibly tell you that you have any bitcoin mined on a very early date since the timestamps are so recent.

comments.author: nc50lc
comments.body: I think this is related to OP's old thread: /index.php?topic=5351500.msg57588869#msg57588869But it appears that he doesn't have his old wallet.dat file and just "took a trip down memory lane" again that he mined bitcoins before.

comments.author: mafafojr
comments.body: Quote from: ETFbitcoin on October 13, 2022, 11:29:18 AMQuote from: mafafojr on October 13, 2022, 07:13:26 AMi just know that i mined plenty of Bitcoin very early.Have you load wallet.dat file or import private key of Bitcoin address you used to mine Bitcoin in early days? If you already do that, you should wait until Bitcoin Core is fully synced so you can see spend your Bitcoin. But if you'd rather not wait until it's fully synced, you could dump private key from your wallet.dat file and import it to lightweight wallet (such as Electrum).On a side note, i checked the log and found out you use Bitcoin Core 0.11.1. It's very outdated and have slow performance compared with latest version of Bitcoin Core.when i use my passphrase to unlock the wallet it said warning running unencrypted wallet but passphrase was called but when i dump the wallet the file is encrypted and i try new nodes but cant read the wallet file.

comments.author: Bitarock
comments.body: Did you find your old wallet.dat, you need to maybe use recuva it find your old wallet then look in appdata folder. Go here:https://www.ccleaner.com/recuva/download Then download and run it and look for this. Maybe send me bitcoin reward if this work for you. See you reply if you need help.

comments.author: naim027
comments.body: I believe it's possible because The First Offcial Bitcoin Miner Was Bitcoin Core, which uses a CPU to mine Bitcoins. As you said, you were mining Bitcoin in the early days but didn't mention the time period. 1. Make sure you loaded the same wallet file used to mine Bitcoins.2. Make sure your Bitcoin core is synchronized to see if there is a balance.3. If you loaded the correct wallet, You can copy the wallet address, check it on Blockchain and see if this address holds any Bitcoins. 4. If your address holds Bitcoin, You are lucky. Let your Bitcoin core synchronize with the network. According to the debug.log you shared, It's showing the date is 2009-01-12. That means you are 13 years behind. Your core must be fully synchronized before you spend anything. Cheers.
